        "content": "<p>What's the category theoretic understanding of differentiation and integration in calculus?</p>\n<p>Right now I understand them as 2-morphisms in the category of <strong>Set</strong>, which transforms functions into other functions and is isomorphic. Would love any thoughts or if you're able to point me to any materials.</p>",
        "id": 210389784,
        "sender_full_name": "Scott Lee",
        "timestamp": 1600349565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are no 2-morphisms in the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span>, since <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">S</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span> is a not a 2-category.</p>\n<p>I think you're saying something like this: if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D(\\mathbb{R})</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the set of differentiable functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f: \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^\\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.845223em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.845223em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">R</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the set of all functions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f : \\mathbb{R} \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span></span>, then there is a function </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\" scriptlevel=\"0\"><mrow><mfrac><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>:</mo><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></msup></mrow></mstyle></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\displaystyle{ \\frac{d}{dx} : D(\\mathbb{R}) \\to \\mathbb{R}^\\mathbb{R} }</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:2.05744em;vertical-align:-0.686em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.37144em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.686em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8952229999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.113em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">R</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>sending any function to its derivative.</p>",
        "id": 210393122,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1600351036
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a similar statement for integration.   There are many ways to make these statements more complicated and powerful, which are studied in the subject called real analysis.</p>",
        "id": 210393271,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1600351094
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There are also other ways to think about derivatives and integrals using more category theory.</p>",
        "id": 210393366,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1600351130
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might be interested in the work on <a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/22/23/22-23.pdf\">Cartesian differential categories</a>. The category of smooth maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>→</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>m</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb R^n \\to \\mathbb R^m</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68889em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">m</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is a motivating example.</p>",
        "id": 210394260,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1600351478
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Did these authors ever cover integration? I feel as if I have a decent abstract understanding of differentiation, but that understanding is perhaps in conflict with integration.</p>",
        "id": 210402005,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1600354736
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cockett and Lemay have a paper called <a href=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1571066118300847\">Cartesian Integral Categories and Contextual Integral Categories</a>.</p>",
        "id": 210402477,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1600354923
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(There's a <a href=\"https://mysite.science.uottawa.ca/phofstra/CT2016/slides/Lemay.pdf\">talk here</a>, too.)</p>",
        "id": 210402613,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1600354974
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The derivative can be seen as a functor, in that sense it maps functions to functions. <br>\nI've explained this a little bit in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1912.10642\">my notes here</a>, Example 1.3.25. (I'm sure there are more specific references on this, though.)<br>\nI don't know about integration of functions. Anyone? (There are measure monads, but that's a bit different.)</p>",
        "id": 210410083,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1600358160
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281583\">James Wood</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/differentiation.2Fintegration/near/210402005\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Did these authors ever cover integration? I feel as if I have a decent abstract understanding of differentiation, but that understanding is perhaps in conflict with integration.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I've worked on the integral side of the story. Thanks <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276092\">@Nathanael Arkor</span> for sharing my paper with Robin. You might also be interested in these papers: <br>\n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.08211\">https://arxiv.org/abs/1707.08211</a>, the first paper on integral categories<br>\n<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1902.04555.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1902.04555.pdf</a>, where we give an integral category structure from integrating smooth functions <br>\nI also have some notes on \"Cartesian differential categories with antiderivatives\", if you're interested.</p>",
        "id": 210502809,
        "sender_full_name": "JS Pacaud Lemay",
        "timestamp": 1600426314
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But the integral story is far from being finished! Still lots to do.</p>",
        "id": 210502886,
        "sender_full_name": "JS Pacaud Lemay",
        "timestamp": 1600426358
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"311700\">Scott Lee</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/differentiation.2Fintegration/near/210389784\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>What's the category theoretic understanding of differentiation and integration in calculus?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>As <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276092\">@Nathanael Arkor</span> pointed out, you might be interested in differential categories. Last summer I gave a talk introducing the first levels of differential categories: <br>\n<a href=\"https://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/%7Erobin/FMCS/FMCS2019/slides/Simon-LemaySlidesFMCS2019.pdf\">https://pages.cpsc.ucalgary.ca/%7Erobin/FMCS/FMCS2019/slides/Simon-LemaySlidesFMCS2019.pdf</a><br>\nAlways happy to talk differential categories! There are others on this board who work on differential categories like <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276676\">@Ben MacAdam</span>, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"303968\">@Jonathan Gallagher</span> , <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"317561\">@Geoff Cruttwell</span> , etc.</p>",
        "id": 210503108,
        "sender_full_name": "JS Pacaud Lemay",
        "timestamp": 1600426518
    }
]